[[File:Opening ceremony (8075978683).jpg|thumb|250px|Opening ceremony of the 1982 Commonwealth Games in Brisbane with mascot [[Matilda (mascot)|Matilda]] winking to the crowd, 30 September 1982]]
The '''1982 Commonwealth Games''' were held in [[Brisbane]], [[Queensland]], [[Australia]] from 30 September to 9 October 1982. The [[1982 Commonwealth Games Opening Ceremony|Opening Ceremony]] was held at the [[Queensland Sport and Athletics Centre|QEII Stadium]] (named for [[Elizabeth II]]), in the Brisbane suburb of [[Nathan, Queensland|Nathan]]. The QEII Stadium was also the venue which was used for the [[Athletics (sport)|athletics]] and [[archery]] competitions during the Games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.austadiums.com/stadiums/stadiums.php?id=5 |title=Queensland Sport and Athletic Centre |website=Austadiums.com |date= |accessdate=2016-08-28}}</ref> Other events were held at the purpose-built [[Sleeman Centre (Brisbane)|Sleeman Sports Complex]] in [[Chandler, Queensland|Chandler]].

The Chairman of the 1982 Commonwealth Games was [[Edward Williams (Queensland judge)|Sir Edward Williams]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Commemorating the life of Sir Edward Williams |url=http://www.sclqld.org.au/schp/exhibitions/williams/brisbane_ambassador.htm |work=2004 |publisher=Supreme Court of Queensland Library |accessdate=7 December 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720110052/http://www.sclqld.org.au/schp/exhibitions/williams/brisbane_ambassador.htm |archivedate=20 July 2008}}</ref>

The 1982 Commonwealth Games Logo was designed by Paulo Ferreira,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.commonwealthgames.org.au/GamesInfo/PastGames/1982/Logo.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-02-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050622091040/http://www.commonwealthgames.org.au/GamesInfo/PastGames/1982/Logo.htm |archivedate=22 June 2005 |df=dmy}}</ref> who was the winner of a nationwide competition held in 1978. The symbol is derived from the form of a bounding kangaroo. The three bands, forming stylized A's (for Australia), are in colours which are common to flags of many Commonwealth countries.

Matilda the [[kangaroo]] [[mascot]] for the 1982 Commonwealth Games was represented by a cartoon kangaroo,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.commonwealthgames.org.au/GamesInfo/PastGames/1982/Mascot.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-02-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050622091126/http://www.commonwealthgames.org.au/GamesInfo/PastGames/1982/Mascot.htm |archivedate=22 June 2005 |df=dmy}}</ref> and a gigantic 13-metre (42 feet 8&nbsp;inches) high mechanical "[[wink]]ing" [[kangaroo]], who travelled around the stadium and [[wink]]ed at the crowd.

The games were officially opened by [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh|The Duke of Edinburgh]] and closed by [[Elizabeth II|The Queen]].

==Host selection==
Bidding for the XII Commonwealth Games was held in [[Montreal]], [[Canada]] at the [[1976 Summer Olympics]]. [[Lagos]], [[Brisbane]], [[Kuala Lumpur]] and [[Birmingham]] were the bidding cities. On 14 July 1976 it was announced that Brisbane had won the rights to stage the Games<ref name="shap">{{Cite book |title=Shaping a city |last=Cole |first=John R. |year=1984 |publisher=William Brooks Queensland |location=Albion, Queensland |isbn=0-85568-619-7 |pages=350–353}}</ref> after the other candidate cities withdrew bids earlier that year.

Brisbane was awarded by default of being the only Candidate City left at the bid election after Birmingham reversed its decision to submit an application.<ref name="shap"/> Nigeria's boycott of the Montreal Summer Olympics made Lagos' bid lobbying impractical.{{Citation needed|date=December 2008}} The Montreal Summer Olympics were plagued with cost overruns and bidding on a sports festival anywhere in the world was not good politically.

==Participating teams==
[[File:Commonwealth games 1982 countries map.PNG|right|thumb|220px|Countries and places which competed at the 1982 games]]
46 Commonwealth nations and territories took part in the 1982 Commonwealth Games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.commonwealthgames.org.au/GamesInfo/PastGames/1982/CompetingCountries.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2006-03-17 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060513045058/http://www.commonwealthgames.org.au/GamesInfo/PastGames/1982/CompetingCountries.htm |archivedate=13 May 2006 |df=dmy}}</ref> A total of 1,583 athletes and 571 officials participated in the event.<ref name="cgc">{{Cite news |url=http://www.brisbanetimes.com.au/queensland/could-the-gold-coast-ever-beat-brisbanes-games-20111110-1n9f6.html |title=Could the Gold Coast ever beat Brisbane's Games? |author=Phil Lutton |accessdate=14 November 2011 |work=Brisbane Times |publisher=Fairfax Media}}</ref> The Griffith University campus was used as an athletes village.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecgf.com/games/tally_country.asp|title=Past Commonwealth Games |publisher=Commonwealth Games Federation|accessdate=25 September 2013}}</ref>

