{{Infobox venue | stadium_name = Javelina Stadium | image = File:DJI 000495645.jpg | location = [[Kingsville, Texas]] | opened = 1950 | owner = [[Texas A&M University-Kingsville]] | operator = [[Texas A&M University-Kingsville]] | surface = Artificial turf | tenants = [[Texas A&M University-Kingsville]] [[Texas A&M–Kingsville Javelinas|Javelinas]] ([[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] [[NCAA Division II|Division II]]) | seating_capacity = 15,000<ref name="javelinaathletics1">{{cite web|url=http://www.javelinaathletics.com/athleticFacilities.cfm?spcode=faci |title=Texas A&M Kingsville - Javelinas |publisher=Javelinaathletics.com |date= |accessdate=2010-11-28 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101108023836/http://www.javelinaathletics.com/athleticFacilities.cfm?spcode=faci |archivedate=2010-11-08 |df= }}</ref> }}
'''Javelina Stadium''' is a [[stadium]] in [[Kingsville, Texas|Kingsville]], [[Texas]]. It is primarily used for [[American football]], and is the home field of [[Texas A&M University-Kingsville]]. The stadium holds 15,000 people<ref name="javelinaathletics1"/> and opened in 1950.
A new scoreboard was installed during the 2006 football season. The scoreboard is the largest scoreboard in NCAA Division II.<ref name="javelinaathletics1"/> The scoreboard is 36 feet wide and 36 feet tall and stands 12 feet off the ground. The video display is over 15 feet tall and 20 feet wide.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://broadcastengineering.com/products/texas-am-daktronics-stadium/ |title=Texas A&M University-Kingsville selects Daktronics for stadium |publisher=Broadcastengineering.com |date= |accessdate=2010-11-28 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110524202048/http://broadcastengineering.com/products/texas-am-daktronics-stadium/ |archivedate=2011-05-24 |df= }}</ref> It features a three camera system and a fully functional production room located under the east side grandstand. It also features a new sound system.
As the home of the Javelinas, the stadium has seen Texas A&I win 7 National Championships in 1959, 1969, 1970, 1974, 1975, 1976 and 1979. Also of note, the Javelinas achieved a 42-game winning streak - undefeated and untied from their last game of 1973 through the third game of 1977.
In addition to college football, the stadium serves as the home of [[Henrietta M. King High School]]'s football team and often selected as a neutral site for high school football playoff games.
From 2001 to 2011, it hosted the [[Cactus Bowl (Division II)|Cactus Bowl]], an all-star game for NCAA Division II seniors.
